flightsim.simconnect.recv
Class RecvSimObjectData

java.lang.Object
  flightsim.simconnect.recv.RecvPacket
      flightsim.simconnect.recv.RecvSimObjectData
Direct Known Subclasses:
RecvClientData, RecvSimObjectDataByType
public class RecvSimObjectData
extends RecvPacket

The base class for all object data received. Calls that will receive a RecvSimObjectData are SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObject(int, int, int, SimConnectPeriod) or SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObjectType(int, int, int, SimObjectType) (as RecvSimObjectDataByType, a subclass of this).

The class provides access to headers members that are available in all received packets and also to defined data correspond to the data definition you set up.

To access defined datas, use getData functions. Each function exists in two variants, a position-less variant where a pointer is kept internally. Avoid multithreads operations on it. The pointer can be reseted with reset(). A variant exists for which the offset of the data, relative to the beginning of the data block is passed. All data are packed in the order you added with SimConnect.addToDataDefinition(int, String, String, flightsim.simconnect.SimConnectDataType, float, int)

If the data was defined with the following datatypes (in this order):

  • SimConnectDataType.FLOAT64
  • SimConnectDataType.STRING256
  • SimConnectDataType.FLOAT32
  • SimConnectDataType.WAYPOINT
    • It can be recovered with the possible sets of instructions:
    • getDataFloat64()()
    • getDataString256()()
    • getDataFloat32()()
    • getWaypoint()()
    Or by specifiying offsets :
    • getDataFloat64()(0)
    • getDataString256()(8)
    • getDataFloat32()(264)
    • getWaypoint()(268)

    Note that variants with explicit offsets don't advance the current pointer. getDataFloat32()(0) followed by getDataFloat32() returns the same data.

    getEntryNumber

    public int getEntryNumber()
    If multiple objects are being returned, this is the index number of this object out of a total of getOutOf(). This will always be 1 if the call was SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObject(int, int, int, SimConnectPeriod, int, int, int, int), and can be 0 or more if the call was SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObjectType(int, int, int, SimObjectType).

    Returns:
    entry number

    getObjectID

    public int getObjectID()
    The object ID. For SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObjectType(int, int, int, SimObjectType) it contains the internal object number, else it contains SimConnectConstants.OBJECT_ID_USER

    Returns:
    object ID

    getOutOf

    public int getOutOf()
    The total number of objects being returned. Note that getEntryNumber() and getOutOf() start with 1 not 0, so if two objects are being returned getEntryNumber() and getOutOf() pairs will be 1,2 and 2,2 for the two objects. This will always be 1 if the call was SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObject(int, int, int, SimConnectPeriod, int, int, int, int), and can be 0 or more if the call was SimConnect.requestDataOnSimObjectType(int, int, int, SimObjectType).

    Returns:
    out of
